                type: "content",
                title: "Introduction: Interpretations and Violations",
                content: "Theory arguments are among the most powerful weapons in competitive debate, but they only work when built on a clear foundation. That foundation starts with two key concepts: interpretations and violations. An interpretation is your claim about what the rules of debate should be—what debaters are obligated to do or not do. A violation is your claim that your opponent has broken that rule.\n\nThink of it like a courtroom. The interpretation is the law, and the violation is the crime. Without a clear law, you can't convict anyone. Without a clear crime, the law is irrelevant. Both pieces must work together for a theory argument to have any persuasive force.\n\nIn this lesson, you'll learn how to craft precise interpretations, identify clear violations, and combine them into theory arguments that judges actually vote on. Whether you're running topicality, fairness shells, or any other procedural argument, the interpretation-violation structure is the backbone of everything.",
