                type: "content",
                title: "Crafting Strong Interpretations",
                content: "A strong interpretation is specific, reasonable, and defensible. Vague interpretations like 'debaters should be fair' give judges nothing to work with. Instead, your interpretation should draw a clear line that the judge can use to evaluate the round. For example: 'The affirmative must defend a specific policy mechanism' or 'Debaters must not introduce new arguments in the second rebuttal.'\n\nThe best interpretations pass what experienced debaters call the 'bright line test.' A bright line is a clear boundary—there's no ambiguity about which side of the line a given action falls on. Compare 'Debaters should be topical' (vague) with 'The affirmative plan must fall within the first definition of the resolution term as defined by Merriam-Webster' (bright line). The second version tells the judge exactly how to evaluate the violation.\n\n**Tips for Writing Interpretations:**\n• Be specific enough that the judge knows exactly what's required\n• Ground your interpretation in a recognizable norm (fairness, education, competitive equity)\n• Make sure your own case doesn't violate your interpretation\n• Consider how your interpretation would affect the broader activity if universally adopted\n• Avoid interpretations so narrow that they only apply to one specific case",
