                content: "Once you have a clear interpretation, you need to show precisely how your opponent has violated it. This is where many debaters get lazy—they state a vague interpretation and then just gesture at their opponent's case, hoping the judge fills in the blanks. Judges don't fill in blanks. You need to do the work.\n\nA well-articulated violation has three components. First, you quote or reference the specific part of your opponent's case or behavior that violates the interpretation. Second, you explain why that specific action crosses the line your interpretation draws. Third, you show that this isn't a borderline case—the violation is clear and undeniable.\n\n**Example of a Weak Violation:**\n'They're not topical because their case doesn't really fit the resolution.'\n\n**Example of a Strong Violation:**\n'My interpretation requires the affirmative to defend increased diplomatic engagement. Their plan focuses entirely on economic sanctions, which is a fundamentally different policy mechanism. The resolution says \"engage,\" not \"sanction.\" Their plan falls outside the topical ground because sanctions are a tool of disengagement, not engagement.'\n\nNotice how the strong version references the specific action (economic sanctions), connects it to the interpretation (diplomatic engagement required), and explains why it clearly crosses the line (sanctions are the opposite of engagement).",
