                content: "After you've stated your interpretation and identified the violation, you need standards—the reasons why your interpretation is the correct one for the round. Standards answer the question: 'Why should the judge adopt your view of what the rules should be?'\n\nThe most common standards are **fairness** and **education**. Under fairness, you argue that your interpretation creates a level playing field. For example: 'My interpretation that the affirmative must specify a funding mechanism is fair because it gives the negative predictable ground to prepare arguments against.' Under education, you argue that your interpretation produces better learning outcomes: 'Requiring debaters to engage with the resolution's core controversy ensures both sides learn about the topic.'\n\n**Other Powerful Standards Include:**\n• **Predictability** — Could debaters reasonably anticipate the arguments they'd face?\n• **Ground** — Does each side have sufficient argumentative territory?\n• **Limits** — Does the interpretation keep the topic manageable?\n• **Reciprocity** — Do both sides face equal burdens?\n• **Real-World Education** — Does the interpretation encourage engaging with real policy questions?\n\nThe key is to explain your standard thoroughly. Don't just say 'fairness.' Explain what kind of fairness, why it matters in this specific context, and how the violation undermines it. A judge who understands your reasoning is far more likely to vote on your theory.",
