                content: "When your opponent runs theory against you, your strongest response is usually a counter-interpretation. A counter-interpretation offers an alternative rule that the judge should adopt instead—one that your behavior doesn't violate. For example, if they say 'The affirmative must defend a single policy mechanism,' you might counter-interpret: 'The affirmative must defend a coherent policy direction, which can include multiple mechanisms.'\n\nThe power of a counter-interpretation is that it shifts the debate from 'Did you violate?' to 'Whose interpretation is better?' This is a much more winnable position because you're no longer on defense—you're offering the judge a choice between two competing visions of what debate should look like.\n\n**Strategies for Counter-Interpretations:**\n• **I Meet** — Show that even under their interpretation, you don't violate. This is the simplest defense.\n• **Counter-Interpret and Turn** — Offer your own interpretation and argue that theirs actually harms fairness or education.\n• **Reasonability** — Argue the judge shouldn't evaluate competing interpretations at all; as long as your behavior is 'reasonable,' theory shouldn't decide the round.\n• **No Voter** — Argue that even if you violate, it shouldn't be a voting issue. The judge should just consider it when weighing arguments.\n\nThe best defenders of theory don't just deny the violation—they make affirmative arguments for why their approach to debate is superior.",
