                content: "Economic topics show up constantly in debate resolutions—trade policy, taxation, minimum wage, healthcare funding, foreign aid, and development. Yet many debaters struggle with economics because the subject feels technical, data-heavy, and full of competing expert opinions. The good news is that you don't need an economics degree to debate these topics effectively. You need a framework for understanding economic arguments and the skills to navigate data responsibly.\n\nEconomic debates are unique because they often hinge on empirical questions: What actually happens when you raise the minimum wage? Does free trade help or hurt developing nations? These questions have real-world data attached to them, but that data is almost always contested. Learning to handle that contestation—rather than pretending one side has all the answers—is what separates strong economic debaters from weak ones.\n\nThis lesson will equip you with strategies for building economic arguments, evaluating economic evidence, and handling the most common economic topics you'll encounter in competition.",
