                content: "Economic evidence is tricky because you can almost always find a study or expert supporting either side of any economic question. This doesn't mean all evidence is equal—some studies are far better than others. Learning to evaluate economic evidence will give you a significant edge in rounds.\n\n**Look for These Quality Indicators:**\n• **Sample size and scope** — A study of 50 businesses in one city tells you less than a meta-analysis of 200 studies across 30 countries. When your opponent cites a small-scale study, point out its limitations.\n• **Peer review and source credibility** — Published in the American Economic Review? Much more credible than a blog post or think tank brief with an obvious political agenda. Always note the source when reading evidence.\n• **Causation vs. correlation** — 'Countries with more free trade have higher GDP' doesn't prove free trade caused the higher GDP. Maybe wealthier countries can afford to trade more freely. This is one of the most common errors in economic debate.\n• **Time frame and context** — A policy that worked in 1990s America might not work in 2020s Nigeria. Economic evidence is context-dependent, and smart debaters exploit outdated or inapplicable evidence.\n\n**When Your Evidence Conflicts With Theirs:**\nDon't just read more cards and hope the judge picks yours. Instead, compare the evidence directly: 'Their study looks at one state over two years. Our meta-analysis covers the entire OECD over two decades. Even if their study is accurate for that state, it doesn't generalize.' This kind of evidence comparison wins rounds.",
