                content: "Framework arguments determine how the judge evaluates the round. If substance is the content of the debate, the framework is the lens through which the judge views that content. Winning the framework often means winning the round, because you get to define what counts as a good argument and what doesn't.\n\nIn Lincoln-Douglas debate, framework is especially central. LD rounds revolve around value premises and criteria, and the debater who successfully establishes the framework essentially tells the judge: 'Here's the standard for deciding who wins. Now let me show you why I meet that standard better.' In policy debate, frameworks appear as standards for weighing impacts, determining the role of the ballot, or establishing what kinds of arguments are legitimate.\n\nThis lesson takes a deep dive into framework strategy and execution. You'll learn how to construct frameworks that give you a strategic advantage, how to attack your opponent's framework, and how to handle framework clashes when both sides offer competing lenses for the round.",
