                content: "A strong framework has three essential components: a clear value or goal, a criterion or standard for measuring that value, and a justification for why this framework should be adopted over alternatives.\n\n**Step 1: Choose Your Value**\nYour value is the ultimate goal your framework pursues. Common values include justice, liberty, human welfare, equality, security, and dignity. Choose a value that connects naturally to your side of the resolution. If you're arguing that governments should provide universal healthcare, 'human welfare' or 'justice' connects more naturally than 'liberty.'\n\n**Step 2: Define Your Criterion**\nYour criterion is the measuring stick—it tells the judge how to determine whether your value is being achieved. For the value of 'justice,' your criterion might be 'protecting the most vulnerable members of society' or 'ensuring equal access to fundamental rights.' The criterion must logically connect to the value AND to your specific arguments. A criterion that connects to your value but doesn't connect to your case is useless.\n\n**Step 3: Justify the Framework**\nExplain why this framework is the right lens for this resolution. Why should the judge evaluate the round through the lens of justice rather than liberty? Why is your criterion the best way to measure that value? This justification often draws on philosophical arguments, real-world examples, or appeals to the resolution's language.\n\n**The Strategic Test:**\nBefore committing to a framework, ask yourself: 'If both sides agree to use this framework, do I still win?' If your opponent's arguments are also strong under your framework, you need a different one. The whole point of framework is to create a lens that favors your position.",
