                type: "content",
                title: "Framework Clash: When Both Sides Have Frameworks",
                content: "In most competitive rounds, both debaters present frameworks, and the judge must decide which one to adopt. Managing this 'framework clash' is one of the most important skills in debate, and it's where many rounds are decided.\n\n**Level 1: Argue Your Framework Is More Appropriate for the Resolution**\nSome resolutions lend themselves to certain frameworks. 'Resolved: Civil disobedience is justified' is clearly asking a moral question, making deontological or virtue-based frameworks more appropriate than pure cost-benefit analysis. Point to the resolution's language and argue that it demands your type of analysis.\n\n**Level 2: Argue Your Framework Has Better Warrant**\nWhose philosophical justification is stronger? If both sides present frameworks, the judge needs a reason to prefer one. Provide that reason by deeply explaining why your value and criterion are correct, not just that they exist.\n\n**Level 3: Argue Your Framework Has Better Real-World Implications**\nEven in a framework debate, judges care about practical consequences. 'If we adopt their framework, it would justify violating human rights whenever doing so produces a slight economic benefit. That can't be the right standard.' Show what happens when their framework is taken to its logical conclusion.\n\n**Level 4: Create a Meta-Framework**\nArgue for a standard by which the judge should evaluate the competing frameworks themselves. 'The judge should prefer the framework that best reflects the resolution's core controversy.' This is advanced but extremely effective when executed well.\n\nThe debater who engages with the framework clash directly—rather than just reading their framework and hoping the judge picks it—wins the vast majority of framework debates.",
