                type: "content",
                title: "Debating While Being Debated",
                content: "Sometimes the social issue you're debating intersects with your own identity. You might be an immigrant debating immigration policy, a person of color debating affirmative action, or a member of a religious minority debating religious freedom. This creates unique challenges and opportunities.\n\n**When You're Personally Connected to the Topic:**\n• Your perspective is valuable and can add authenticity to your arguments\n• Be strategic about when and how to share personal connections—it's not required, and you should never feel pressured to disclose\n• Remember that winning the debate doesn't require you to validate every aspect of your personal experience\n• If debating a position you personally disagree with (as assigned side), separate your role as a debater from your personal views. You can say: 'While I'm assigned to argue this position...'\n\n**When Your Opponent is Personally Connected:**\n• Treat their perspective with respect regardless of your argument's position\n• Engage with the substance of their arguments, not their identity\n• Never use someone's personal connection to dismiss their argument ('You're biased because this affects you')\n• Remember that lived experience is a form of evidence, even if it has limitations\n\n**Maintaining Your Well-Being:**\nDebating topics that affect you personally can be emotionally taxing. It's okay to take breaks, to ask for support, and to process your feelings after a difficult round. Being a strong debater doesn't mean being emotionally invulnerable. Many of the best debaters on social issues are passionate precisely because the topics matter to them personally.",
