                type: "content",
                title: "Value Debate in Cross-Examination",
                content: "Cross-examination is one of the most underused tools for winning the value debate. While many debaters use cross-ex to attack substantive arguments, targeting your opponent's value structure in cross-ex can be even more effective because it sets up your entire rebuttal strategy.\n\n**Questions That Expose Value-Criterion Gaps:**\n• 'Can you give me a real-world example where your criterion would be met but your value wouldn't be achieved?' — If they can, their criterion is flawed. If they can't, they may be unprepared for the question.\n• 'Does your criterion apply to every person equally, or are some people excluded?' — Exposes limitations in their framework.\n• 'If we had to choose between your value and mine, why should yours take priority?' — Forces them to engage with value comparison directly.\n\n**Questions That Build Your Framework Attacks:**\n• 'You said your value is justice. Do you think justice can ever require limiting individual liberty?' — Their answer sets up your argument either way.\n• 'Your criterion is maximizing welfare. Does that mean it's okay to harm a small group if it benefits a larger group?' — Exposes the classic utilitarian weakness.\n• 'How do you measure whether your criterion has been met?' — If they can't explain measurement, the criterion is too vague to be useful.\n\n**Cross-Ex Discipline:**\nKeep cross-ex questions short and closed-ended. Don't let your opponent give speeches. If they start rambling, politely redirect: 'I appreciate the context, but can you answer my specific question?' Document their answers so you can reference them in your rebuttal: 'In cross-ex, my opponent admitted that their criterion could justify harming minorities for the majority's benefit. That's exactly the problem with their framework.'",
