                content: "Once you're comfortable constructing and attacking value structures, these advanced strategies can elevate your performance in competitive rounds.\n\n**Value Agreement, Criterion Battle:**\nSometimes both debaters choose the same value—most commonly justice. When this happens, the entire debate shifts to the criterion level. Prepare for this by having multiple criteria ready for your most common values. If your opponent also picks justice, you need to win why your criterion better measures justice.\n\n**The Floating Criterion:**\nA floating criterion isn't explicitly stated in your case but emerges from your arguments. Instead of saying 'My criterion is protecting autonomy,' your contentions build toward that conclusion so the judge sees it naturally. This is advanced and risky—if the judge doesn't see the implicit criterion, your framework lacks structure. But when it works, it feels more organic and less formulaic.\n\n**Criterion Stacking:**\nPresent your criterion as having multiple 'prongs' or components. 'My criterion has two parts: first, the policy must not violate fundamental rights, and second, among rights-respecting options, we should choose the one that produces the best outcomes.' This creates a layered evaluation that's harder to attack because opponents must beat both parts.\n\n**Value Exclusion:**\nArgue that your opponent's value simply doesn't belong in this debate. 'The resolution asks about government obligation, which is inherently about justice. Their value of individual happiness is a personal preference, not a standard for evaluating government policy. The resolution's language excludes their framework.' This is aggressive but can be highly effective when the resolution's wording supports it.\n\nThese strategies require practice and sophistication. Start with solid value-criterion construction and only move to advanced techniques once your fundamentals are strong.",
