                type: "content",
                title: "Review: Value Premises and Criteria in LD",
                content: "In Lincoln-Douglas debate, the value premise and criterion are the foundation of your case. They tell the judge what matters most and how to measure it.\n\n**Selecting Values:**\nYour value should feel inevitable given the resolution. Common values include justice, liberty, human dignity, societal welfare, and equality. Avoid values that sound impressive but don't connect to the resolution, and be wary of values your opponent can easily co-opt.\n\n**Crafting Criteria:**\nYour criterion must pass the connection test: it must link upward to your value (explaining how to measure it) and downward to your contentions (your arguments must demonstrate meeting the criterion). Ground criteria in recognized philosophical traditions—Rawls, Kant, Mill—for intellectual weight. Specificity matters: 'protecting the least advantaged' is actionable; 'being fair' is not.\n\n**Attacking Value Structures:**\n• Attack the value-criterion link (their criterion doesn't measure their value)\n• Attack the criterion-contention link (their arguments don't meet their criterion)\n• Use value hierarchy arguments (your value is more fundamental)\n• Turn their framework (under their own criterion, you win)\n\n**Cross-Examination for Value Debate:**\nAsk for examples, test the criterion's limits, and document admissions for rebuttal use. Cross-ex is one of the most effective tools for winning the value debate.\n\n**Advanced Strategies:**\nValue agreement shifts the debate to criteria. Criterion stacking creates layered evaluation. Value exclusion argues their framework doesn't fit the resolution. Master fundamentals before attempting advanced techniques.",
